    "recap_headline": "Georgia Southern University",
    "recap_text": "Harrisonburg, Va. \u2014\nThe Georgia Southern baseball team (5-12, 0-1 SBC) fell to James Madison (8-8, 1-0 SBC) by a 14-6 margin on Friday afternoon in their first conference game of 2026.\nHOW IT HAPPENED:\nThe Dukes got the first run of a 2026 Sun Belt conference\u00a0game\u00a0to start the day in their first, as a leadoff double from Kyle Langley put a Duke in scoring position. He later came around to score following two deep fly balls to make it 1-0.\nA leadoff single from\nBryson Trammell\nin the second later saw\nBrady Christman\ndeliver a line drive to the gap. The Eagles were too aggressive on the bases, ending the inning with a throwdown at home.\nThree runs were added on by JMU in the second off three hits, including two doubles, to extend their early advantage to 4-0.\nThe Eagles' woke up their bats after a hit batter and consecutive singles from\nJames McCoy\nand\nJack Myers\nloaded the bags.\nSean White\nput Southern on the board after his RBI-groundout.\nThe momentum kept going into the fourth as a leadoff single from\nMax Prozny\nput an Eagle on. The first pitch\nNico Senese\nsaw in his AB right after was a deep fly into left-center that sailed over the wall for a two-run homer, his first of the season.\nThe Eagles completed the comeback later that inning\u00a0after\nBrady Christman\nreached on a walk and advanced himself to third. McCoy brought him home from a sac-fly, evening the game at four each.\nThe Dukes responded in the bottom of the fifth\u00a0using a walk, two singles and a sac-bunt to put up two runs with only one retired off the bunt.\nJMU added six more runs in the sixth, all of which were unearned after a fielding error from Senese. A hit batter followed by an errant pickoff attempt put both runners in scoring position. Two singles, a sac-fly and back-to-back homers from Jack Cannizzaro and Wyatt Campbell extended the Dukes' lead to 12-4.\nThe Eagles got one back after a\nSean White\nsolo homer, a ball that rode the wind and traveled 418 feet over the left field wall.\nThe Dukes immediately got theirs back in the next half inning, as Ike Schmidly had a two-run homer, their third of the day,\u00a0 to make it 14-5.\nIn the ninth,\nSean White\nsingled in the infield to plate his second RBI of the day, but was all the Eagles could muster in the final frame.\nNOTES:\nThe homer from Senese would be his first of the season and fourth at Southern. His last two homers came against the Dukes, with his prior one coming on May 3rd of 2025.\nSean White's\nhomer in the seventh extended his current hitting streak to now seven games. The senior also has had base knocks in eleven of his last dozen contests.\nJayden White\nmade his third appearance of his career, going a full inning without allowing any hits or runs.\nMcCoy and Prozny's bats stayed hot as they both had two hits on the afternoon. McCoy has had multi-hits in three of his last four games, with Prozny doing the same in four of his last five.\nUP NEXT:\nThe Dukes and Eagles continue their weekend series with the same first pitch to today's contest at 4 PM on Saturday, March 14th."
